t-18","page_id":"/docs/guides/do-and-dont","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/do-and-dont#-keep-the-tuple-close-to-the-boundary","content":"Wrap I/O once, then pass domain values through the rest of the function."},"64":{"id":"/docs/guides/do-and-dont-19","page_id":"/docs/guides/do-and-dont","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/do-and-dont#-wrap-every-line-in-safetry","content":"If a function is already synchronous and pure, let it stay ordinary code."},"65":{"id":"/docs/guides/do-and-dont-20","page_id":"/docs/guides/do-and-dont","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/do-and-dont#-pass-the-signal-all-the-way-into-the-io-api","content":"Cancellation only matters when the transport or subprocess actually sees the signal."},"66":{"id":"/docs/guides/do-and-dont-21","page_id":"/docs/guides/do-and-dont","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/do-and-dont#-assume-a-task-group-can-kill-arbitrary-cpu-work","content":"`AbortSignal` is cooperative. If your code ignores it, the work keeps running."},"67":{"id":"/docs/guides/do-and-dont-22","page_id":"/docs/guides/do-and-dont","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/do-and-dont#-retry-transport-failures-and-transient-infrastructure-noise","content":"Network timeouts, brief lock contentions, and flaky subprocess startup are reasonable candidates."},"68":{"id":"/docs/guides/do-and-dont-23","page_id":"/docs/guides/do-and-dont","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/do-and-dont#-retry-validation-failures-or-deterministic-domain-errors","content":"If the request shape is bad on attempt one, it will still be bad on attempt three."},"69":{"id":"/docs/guides/do-and-dont-24","page_id":"/docs/guides/do-and-dont","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/do-and-dont#-bind-stable-dependencies-at-the-edge","content":"Loggers, repositories, mailers, and feature flags are good candidates for `inject()`."},"70":{"id":"/docs/guides/do-and-dont-25","page_id":"/docs/guides/do-and-dont","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/do-and-dont#-build-a-hidden-service-locator-around-it","content":"If the dependencies are not obvious from the function signature, the code gets harder to review."},"71":{"id":"/docs/guides/do-and-dont-26","page_id":"/docs/guides/do-and-dont","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/do-and-dont#-use-async-context-for-request-scoped-metadata","content":"Trace spans, request IDs, user sessions, or a transaction handle fit well."},"72":{"id":"/docs/guides/do-and-dont-27","page_id":"/docs/guides/do-and-dont","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/do-and-dont#-use-async-context-as-your-application-container","content":"Configuration and stable dependencies should still be explicit."},"73":{"id":"/docs/guides/do-and-dont-28","page_id":"/docs/guides/do-and-dont","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/do-and-dont#boundaries","content":"A good rule of thumb: tuples are for work you expect to fail sometimes, thrown exceptions are for code that truly cannot continue. If a boundary requires exceptions, convert at that one spot with `unwrap()` and move on."},"74":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","type":"page","content":"Quickstart","breadcrumbs":["Docs","Guides","Guides"],"tags":[],"url":"/docs/guides/quickstart"},"75":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-0","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart","content":"Get a Yieldless application flow working with tuple errors, cancellation, and one realistic boundary."},"76":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-1","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#install","content":"Install"},"77":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-2","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#step-1-stop-throwing-for-routine-failures","content":"Step 1: stop throwing for routine failures"},"78":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-3","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#step-2-group-related-work-under-one-cancellation-signal","content":"Step 2: group related work under one cancellation signal"},"79":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-4","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#step-3-add-retries-where-the-outside-world-is-unreliable","content":"Step 3: add retries where the outside world is unreliable"},"80":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-5","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#step-4-keep-the-edges-boring","content":"Step 4: keep the edges boring"},"81":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-6","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#a-full-request-flow","content":"A full request flow"},"82":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-7","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#where-to-go-next","content":"Where to go next"},"83":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-8","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart","content":"The fastest way to understand Yieldless is to wire the core pieces together:"},"84":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-9","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart","content":"`yieldless/error` to keep failures in tuple form"},"85":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-10","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart","content":"`yieldless/task` and `yieldless/all` to fan work out and cancel siblings cleanly"},"86":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-11","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart","content":"`yieldless/retry` to handle noisy infrastructure without leaking timers"},"87":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-12","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart","content":"`yieldless/signal` to enforce one clear deadline on the whole boundary"},"88":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-13","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#install","content":"TypeScript 5.5+ is the target baseline. The package is compiled with `isolatedDeclarations` enabled."},"89":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-14","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#step-1-stop-throwing-for-routine-failures","content":"`safeTry()` and `safeTrySync()` let you treat common failures as data instead of exception control flow."},"90":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-15","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#step-1-stop-throwing-for-routine-failures","content":"That pattern is the center of the library. Every module is designed to fit back into the same `[error, value]` shape."},"91":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-16","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#step-2-group-related-work-under-one-cancellation-signal","content":"`runTaskGroup()` gives you a shared abort signal and sibling failure propagation."},"92":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-17","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#step-2-group-related-work-under-one-cancellation-signal","content":"If `readRefs()` throws, the group aborts the shared signal, waits for `readStatus()` to settle, and then rethrows the original failure.\nIf the request or UI flow already has an `AbortSignal`, pass it in so the whole group inherits upstream cancellation."},"93":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-18","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#step-2-group-related-work-under-one-cancellation-signal","content":"When the work is a list rather than a few named tasks, use `mapLimit()` to keep pressure on the outside world under control."},"94":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-19","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#step-2-group-related-work-under-one-cancellation-signal","content":"The result order matches the input order, and the first tuple error aborts the remaining in-flight work."},"95":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-20","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#step-3-add-retries-where-the-outside-world-is-unreliable","content":"Retries should stay close to transport boundaries: HTTP, queues, database connections, and subprocesses that can legitimately fail for transient reasons."},"96":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-21","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#step-3-add-retries-where-the-outside-world-is-unreliable","content":"The retry loop respects `AbortSignal`, so if a parent task group is canceled, the pending backoff timer is canceled too."},"97":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-22","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#step-4-keep-the-edges-boring","content":"When a boundary needs a firm time budget, derive one signal and pass it through the whole call chain."},"98":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-23","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#step-4-keep-the-edges-boring","content":"The package ships adapters for common backend boundaries:"},"99":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-24","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#step-4-keep-the-edges-boring","content":"`yieldless/schema` keeps validators in tuple form"},"100":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-25","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#step-4-keep-the-edges-boring","content":"`yieldless/router` turns tuple handlers into HTTP responses"},"101":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-26","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#step-4-keep-the-edges-boring","content":"`yieldless/ipc` preserves tuple results across Electron IPC"},"102":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-27","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#step-4-keep-the-edges-boring","content":"`yieldless/node` wraps filesystem and child-process work"},"103":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-28","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#where-to-go-next","content":"Read Design Rules before you spread the tuple style across a large codebase."},"104":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-29","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#where-to-go-next","content":"Read Do and Don't if you are moving a team onto the library and want the conventions to stay sharp."},"105":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-30","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#where-to-go-next","content":"Use the reference section when you already know what module you need."},"106":{"id":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work","page_id":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work","type":"page","content":"Bounded Batch Work","breadcrumbs":["Docs","Recipes","Recipes"],"tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work"},"107":{"id":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work-0","page_id":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work","content":"Process lists of API, filesystem, or subprocess work without unbounded parallelism."},"108":{"id":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work-1","page_id":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work#refresh-several-repositories","content":"Refresh several repositories"},"109":{"id":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work-2","page_id":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work#why-this-is-friendlier","content":"Why this is friendlier"},"110":{"id":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work-3","page_id":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work","content":"This recipe is for the common \"do this for every item\" path: refresh every repo, fetch every avatar, resize every image, or inspect every file. The work is independent, but starting it all at once can make a user's machine or an upstream service miserable."},"111":{"id":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work-4","page_id":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work","content":"Use `mapLimit()` when you want tuple errors, shared cancellation, stable output order, and a hard ceiling on active work."},"112":{"id":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work-5","page_id":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work#why-this-is-friendlier","content":"Output order matches `repositories`, so UI code does not need to sort the result back into place."},"113":{"id":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work-6","page_id":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work#why-this-is-friendlier","content":"The first tuple error aborts in-flight work and stops starting new items."},"114":{"id":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work-7","page_id":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work#why-this-is-friendlier","content":"A parent `AbortSignal` can cancel the whole batch when the user navigates away."},"115":{"id":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work-8","page_id":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work#why-this-is-friendlier","content":"`concurrency` is explicit, so expensive work stays polite by default."},"116":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client","type":"page","content":"Electron Git Client","breadcrumbs":["Docs","Recipes","Recipes"],"tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client"},"117":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client-0","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client","content":"An end-to-end shape for a desktop Git app using IPC tuples, abortable subprocesses, and typed renderer calls."},"118":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client-1","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client#main-process-contract","content":"Main-process contract"},"119":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client-2","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client#main-process-implementation","content":"Main-process implementation"},"120":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client-3","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client#preload-bridge","content":"Preload bridge"},"121":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client-4","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client#renderer-usage","content":"Renderer usage"},"122":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client-5","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client#why-this-boundary-feels-cleaner","content":"Why this boundary feels cleaner"},"123":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client-6","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client","content":"Yieldless fits Electron well because the important boundaries in an Electron app are all failure-heavy: the renderer asks for work through IPC, the main process touches the filesystem, the main process launches long-running child processes like `git clone`."},"124":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client-7","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client#main-process-implementation","content":"If the window is torn down or a parent task group is canceled, the subprocess is aborted through Node's native child-process signal handling."},"125":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client-8","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client#why-this-boundary-feels-cleaner","content":"The renderer never depends on Electron's lossy thrown-error conversion."},"126":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client-9","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client#why-this-boundary-feels-cleaner","content":"The main process can use the same tuple style it uses everywhere else."},"127":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client-10","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client#why-this-boundary-feels-cleaner","content":"Long-running Git subprocesses can be canceled as soon as the UI no longer cares about them."},"128":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","type":"page","content":"Electron PR Review Workbench","breadcrumbs":["Docs","Recipes","Recipes"],"tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench"},"129":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench-0","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","content":"A practical architecture for a GitHub pull-request review desktop app using tuples in the right places and ordinary UI state in the renderer."},"130":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench-1","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench#main-process-contract","content":"Main-process contract"},"131":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench-2","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench#main-process-implementation","content":"Main-process implementation"},"132":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench-3","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench#preload-bridge","content":"Preload bridge"},"133":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench-4","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench#renderer-state","content":"Renderer state"},"134":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench-5","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench#why-this-fits-pr-review-tools-well","content":"Why this fits PR review tools well"},"135":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench-6","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench#rule-of-thumb","content":"Rule of thumb"},"136":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench-7","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","content":"If you are building a GitHub PR review app in Electron, Yieldless fits best in the main process, preload bridge, and service layer. It is less useful as the shape of your React component state."},"137":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench-8","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","content":"That distinction matters:"},"138":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench-9","page_